        <h4 class="title">Types of stroke

            Ischemic Stroke – This type of stroke occurs when a blood vessel in the brain is suddenly blocked by a blood
            clot, preventing blood from being delivered to the brain. Blood clots often form due to a condition called
            arteriosclerosis. With this condition, the lumen of blood vessels narrows, forming fatty blood clots. More
            than 80 percent of strokes are of this type.



            Hemorrhagic stroke – usually more serious than ischemic stroke. The cause is sudden rupture and bleeding of
            cerebral blood vessels. This type of stroke is usually caused by high blood pressure or an aneurysm. An
            aneurysm is a balloon-like swollen sac formed in an artery, causing the blood vessel to weaken and expand,
            causing it to rupture.

        </h4>
